#Summary1=(human1) This proof demonstrates that if AB is a second bimedial line divided at C into its medials, and DE is a rational line where DEFG = AB² is applied to DE such that DG is its breadth, then DG is a third binomial straight line.

#Summary2=(claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022) The proof demonstrates that if AB is a second bimedial straight line divided at point C, with AC > CB, and DEFG equals AB² applied to a rational line DE, then DG must be a third binomial straight line through geometric constructions and properties of medial, rational, and commensurable magnitudes.

#Summary3=(gpt4o) This mathematical proof demonstrates that a straight line DG, derived from applying a square equal to a second bimedial line AB to another straight line DE, is a third binomial line using classical geometric propositions related to commensurability and the properties of binomial lines.

#Summary4=(Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct) This mathematical proof demonstrates that a certain line DG is a third binomial straight line, deriving this result through a series of geometric and algebraic transformations and commensurability theorems.

#Summary5=(Qwen2.5-3B-Instruct) The document proves DG to be a third binomial straight line through detailed geometric constructions and properties, concluding with intermediate steps showing commensurability and incommensurability relationships.
#Text=Proof
#Text=Let AB be a second bimedial straight line divided into its medials at C .
#Text=Let AC > CB .
#Text=Let DE be a rational straight line .
#Text=Let DEFG equal to AB2 be applied to DE producing DG as its breadth .
#Text=It is to be demonstrated that DG is a third binomial straight line .
#Text=From Proposition 4 of Book II : Square of Sum : AB2 = AC2 + CB2 + 2 ⋅ AC ⋅ CB
#Text=Let the rectangle DH be applied to DE such that DH = AC2 .
#Text=Let the rectangle KL be applied to DE such that KL = BC2 .
#Text=Then the rectangle MF is equal to 2 ⋅ AC ⋅ CB .
#Text=Let MG be bisected at N .
#Text=Let NO be drawn parallel to ML ( or GF , which is the same thing ) .
#Text=Therefore each of the rectangles MO and NF equals AC ⋅ CB .
#Text=We have that AB is a second bimedial which has been divided into its medials at C .
#Text=Therefore , by definition , AC and CB are medial straight lines which are commensurable in square only such that AC ⋅ CB is a medial rectangle .
#Text=Thus , by definition , AC2 and CB2 are also medial .

#Text=From : Proposition 15 of Book X : Commensurability of Sum of Commensurable Magnitudes and : Porism to Proposition 23 of Book X : Straight Line Commensurable with Medial Straight Line is Medial it follows that : DL is medial .
#Text=We have that DL has been applied to the rational straight line DE .
#Text=Therefore from Proposition 22 of Book X : Square on Medial Straight Line : MD is rational and incommensurable in length with DE .
#Text=For the same reason :
#Text=MG is also rational straight line and incommensurable in length with ML , which equals DE .
#Text=Therefore each of DM and MG is rational straight line and incommensurable in length with DE .
#Text=We have that AC is incommensurable in length with CB .
#Text=Also : AC : CB = AC2 : AC ⋅ CB
#Text=Therefore by Proposition 11 of Book X : Commensurability of Elements of Proportional Magnitudes : AC2 is incommensurable with AC ⋅ CB .

#Text=Hence by : Proposition 12 of Book X : Commensurability is Transitive Relation and : Proposition 13 of Book X : Commensurable Magnitudes are Incommensurable with Same Magnitude it follows that : AC2 + CB2 is incommensurable with 2 ⋅ AC ⋅ CB .
#Text=That is : DL is incommensurable with MF .

#Text=So from : Proposition 1 of Book VI : Areas of Triangles and Parallelograms Proportional to Base and : Proposition 11 of Book X : Commensurability of Elements of Proportional Magnitudes it follows that : DM is incommensurable in length with MG .
#Text=But DM and MG are rational straight lines which are incommensurable in length with each other .
#Text=Therefore by definition DG is binomial .
#Text=It remains to be proved that DG is a third binomial straight line .
#Text=From Lemma to Proposition 60 of Book X : Square on Binomial Straight Line applied to Rational Straight Line : AC2 + CB2 > 2 ⋅ AC ⋅ CB Therefore DL > MF .
#Text=From Proposition 1 of Book VI : Areas of Triangles and Parallelograms Proportional to Base : DM > MG
#Text=Since : AC2 is commensurable with CB2 it follows that : DH is commensurable with KL .

#Text=So from : Proposition 1 of Book VI : Areas of Triangles and Parallelograms Proportional to Base and : Proposition 11 of Book X : Commensurability of Elements of Proportional Magnitudes it follows that : DK is commensurable in length with KM .
#Text=Also DK ⋅ KM = MN2 .

#Text=Thus from Lemma to Proposition 17 of Book X : Condition for Commensurability of Roots of Quadratic Equation : DM2 is greater than MG2 by the square on a straight line commensurable in length with DM .
#Text=Also :
#Text=Neither DM nor MG is commensurable in length with DE .
#Text=Therefore DG is a third binomial straight line . ■
